        <section id="candidates" class="pt-16 -mt-16 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-sky-700 mb-8 text-center">Information for Candidates</h2>
            <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed">
                    For international childcare professionals aspiring to work in Australia, meeting specific eligibility criteria is paramount. This section provides a detailed breakdown of the key requirements for candidates seeking sponsorship, including qualifications, work experience, English language proficiency, health and character checks, and the crucial role of a confirmed job offer. Understanding these aspects in depth will help you prepare a strong visa application.
                </p>
                 <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div x-data="{ open: false }" class="bg-amber-50 p-4 rounded-lg shadow">
                        <button @click="open = !open" class="flex justify-between items-center w-full text-left">
                            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600">Qualifications</h3>
                            <span x-text="open ? '−' : '+'" class="text-2xl text-sky-600"></span>
                        </button>
                        <div x-show="open" x-cloak class="mt-3 text-neutral-700 space-y-2">
                            <p>To be eligible for skilled migration as a childcare professional in Australia, you must hold qualifications that are recognized and deemed equivalent to Australian standards. The minimum qualification generally required for a Child Care Worker (ANZSCO 421111) is a Certificate III in Early Childhood Education and Care (CHC30121).</p>
                            <p>For leadership roles or specialized positions, a Diploma of Early Childhood Education and Care (CHC50121) may be required. Early Childhood Teachers (ECTs) typically need a relevant Bachelor's degree or higher qualification in early childhood education.</p>
                            <p><strong>ACECQA Assessment:</strong> For all overseas qualifications, an assessment by the Australian Children's Education and Care Quality Authority (ACECQA) is mandatory. ACECQA assesses whether your overseas qualifications are equivalent to the relevant Australian qualifications required for working in regulated ECEC services. This assessment is a critical step in the visa application process, as a positive outcome is often required for skills assessment and visa eligibility.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div x-data="{ open: false }" class="bg-amber-50 p-4 rounded-lg shadow">
                        <button @click="open = !open" class="flex justify-between items-center w-full text-left">
                            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600">Work Experience</h3>
                            <span x-text="open ? '−' : '+'" class="text-2xl text-sky-600"></span>
                        </button>
                        <div x-show="open" x-cloak class="mt-3 text-neutral-700 space-y-2">
                            <p>For the Skills in Demand (SID) 482 visa, candidates are generally required to have at least 1 year of full-time equivalent work experience in their nominated occupation or a closely related field. This experience must have been gained within the last 5 years. "Full-time equivalent" means working at least 38 hours per week, or a pro-rata equivalent if part-time.</p>
                            <p>For Early Childhood Teachers (ECTs), a minimum of 1 year of full-time, paid employment experience is required. It's important that this experience is relevant to the duties of the nominated occupation as defined by ANZSCO (Australian and New Zealand Standard Classification of Occupations).</p>
                            <p>Formal placements, internships, or apprenticeships can count towards this work experience requirement if they were part of a CRICOS registered course (Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students) and involved structured workplace learning relevant to the occupation.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div x-data="{ open: false }" class="bg-amber-50 p-4 rounded-lg shadow">
                        <button @click="open = !open" class="flex justify-between items-center w-full text-left">
                            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600">English Language Proficiency</h3>
                            <span x-text="open ? '−' : '+'" class="text-2xl text-sky-600"></span>
                        </button>
                        <div x-show="open" x-cloak class="mt-3 text-neutral-700 space-y-2">
                            <p>Demonstrating English language proficiency is a mandatory requirement for most Australian skilled migration visas, including the SID 482 visa. Common tests accepted include:</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-1">
                                <li><strong>IELTS (International English Language Testing System):</strong> Typically a minimum overall score with no band less than a specified level (e.g., 5.0 or 6.0 in each of the four components: listening, reading, writing, and speaking).</li>
                                <li><strong>PTE Academic (Pearson Test of English Academic):</strong> Equivalent scores are accepted.</li>
                                <li>Other tests like OET, TOEFL iBT, and Cambridge English Advanced (CAE) may also be accepted.</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p class="mt-2">For Early Childhood Teachers (ECTs), ACECQA often has higher specific English language requirements for skills assessment, such as an IELTS Academic score of at least 7.0 for Reading and Writing, and 8.0 for Speaking and Listening.</p>
                            <p>Designated Area Migration Agreement (DAMA) pathways may offer concessions or exemptions on English language requirements, making them more accessible for candidates who might not meet the standard thresholds. Exemptions from English testing may also apply to citizens of certain English-speaking countries (e.g., UK, USA, Canada, New Zealand, Ireland) or those who have completed specific tertiary study in English.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                     <div x-data="{ open: false }" class="bg-amber-50 p-4 rounded-lg shadow">
                        <button @click="open = !open" class="flex justify-between items-center w-full text-left">
                            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600">Health and Character Requirements</h3>
                            <span x-text="open ? '−' : '+'" class="text-2xl text-sky-600"></span>
                        </button>
                        <div x-show="open" x-cloak class="mt-3 text-neutral-700 space-y-2">
                            <p>All visa applicants must meet Australia's health and character requirements. This involves:</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-1">
                                <li><strong>Medical Examinations:</strong> Undergoing mandatory medical examinations conducted by a panel physician approved by the Australian government. This includes general health checks, chest X-rays, and blood tests to ensure you do not pose a public health risk.</li>
                                <li><strong>Police Clearance Certificates:</strong> Providing police clearance certificates from your home country and any other country where you have lived for 12 months or more in the last 10 years since turning 16. These checks assess your criminal history and ensure you meet Australia's character requirements.</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p class="mt-2">In addition to federal immigration requirements, working with children in Queensland requires a Queensland Working with Children Check, commonly known as a "Blue Card." This is a separate state-based check that assesses the suitability of individuals to work with children and young people. You will need to apply for and obtain a Blue Card once you are in Queensland and before commencing work in a childcare setting.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                     <div x-data="{ open: false }" class="bg-amber-50 p-4 rounded-lg shadow">
                        <button @click="open = !open" class="flex justify-between items-center w-full text-left">
                            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600">Job Offer and Nomination</h3>
                            <span x-text="open ? '−' : '+'" class="text-2xl text-sky-600"></span>
                        </button>
                        <div x-show="open" x-cloak class="mt-3 text-neutral-700 space-y-2">
                            <p>A confirmed job offer from an approved Australian employer is an essential prerequisite for most skilled migration visas, including the SID 482 visa. You cannot apply for these visas without an employer first nominating you for a specific position.</p>
                            <p>Once an employer has received their Standard Business Sponsorship (SBS) approval and has nominated you for a position, they will provide you with a Transaction Reference Number (TRN) or a similar identifier. This TRN is crucial as you will need it to link your individual visa application to your employer's nomination. The nomination details, including the occupation, salary, and location, must align with your visa application to ensure a successful outcome.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="mt-8 bg-stone-50 p-6 rounded-lg shadow">
